III. DISPARITY TRANSFORMATION
DT [35] aims at transforming a disparity image into a quasi bird‚Äôs eye view, so that the pixels of drivable areas possess similar values, while they differ greatly from those of the road damages/anomalies [36]. The expression of DT is as follows:

Dt = Do ‚àí f (p, a, Œ∏) + Œ¥,

(1)

where Do is the original disparity image; Dt is the transformed disparity image; f is a non-linear function representing the disparities in the drivable area; p = (u; v) is an image pixel; a = (a0; a1) stores the road proÔ¨Åle model coefÔ¨Åcients; Œ∏ is the stereo rig roll angle; and Œ¥ is a constant set to ensure that the transformed disparity values are non-negative. Œ∏ can be obtained by minimizing [37]

‚àí1
E(Œ∏) = d d ‚àí d T(Œ∏) T(Œ∏) T(Œ∏) T(Œ∏) d, (2)

where T = [1k, v cos Œ∏ ‚àí u sin Œ∏]; d = (d1; ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ; dk) is a k-entry vector of disparities; u = (u1; ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ; uk) is a k-entry vector of horizontal coordinates; and v = (v1; ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ; vk) denotes a k-entry vector of vertical coordinates. a can be estimated
using [35]

‚àí1

a(Œ∏) = T(Œ∏) T(Œ∏) T(Œ∏) d.

(3)

In this paper, we Ô¨Årst utilize the road segmentation approach proposed in [38] to detect a coarse drivable area through vdisparity image analysis and disparity image segmentation. The disparities in the detected coarse drivable area are then used to estimate a and Œ∏ for disparity image transformation, as shown in Fig. 2.

IV. DYNAMIC FUSION MODULE
In this section, we Ô¨Årst introduce our proposed DFM, which can generate fused features effectively and efÔ¨Åciently, as illustrated in Fig. 3. Then, we explain how to employ our DFM in data-fusion networks for semantic segmentation, and introduce our DFM-RTFNet, as shown in Fig. 1.
Given an RGB feature Fr of size H √ó W √ó C and a feature to be fused Ft of the same size, the basic concept of dynamic fusion is to produce a dynamic kernel W based on Ft and then apply W on Fr to output the fused feature Ff of H √óW √óC , as shown in Fig. 3 (a). This process can be regarded as an

