VI. CONCLUSION
In this paper, we conducted a comprehensive study on drivable area and road anomaly detection for mobile robots, including building a benchmark and proposing an effective and efÔ¨Åcient data-fusion strategy named DFM. Experimental results veriÔ¨Åed that our transformed disparity images could enable drivable areas exhibit similar values, which could beneÔ¨Åt networks for drivable area and road anomaly detection. Moreover, our proposed DFM can effectively generate fused features with high activation values in critical areas using content-dependent and spatially variant kernels, and thus improve the overall detection performance. Compared with the SOTA networks, our DFM-RTFNet can produce more accurate and robust results for drivable area and road anomaly detection. Hence, it is suitable to be implemented in mobile robots in practice. Furthermore, our DFM-RTFNet achieves competitive performance on the KITTI road benchmark. We
